Here's how to handle save/restore of draft text using MAUI's lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resuming += OnResuming;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Stopped += OnStopped;

        // Restore any saved draft on page load
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void OnStopped(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        SaveDraft();
    }

    private void OnResuming(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }

    ~NotePage()
    {
        if (App.Current?.Windows.Count > 0)
        {
            App.Current.Windows[0].Resuming -= OnResuming;
            App.Current.Windows[0].Stopped -= OnStopped;
        }
    }
}
```

**In your `NotePage.xaml`:**

```xml
<Editor x:Name="NoteEditor"
        Placeholder="Start typing your note..." />
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Stopped`** fires when the app goes to the background — save here.
- **`Window.Resuming`** fires when it comes back — restore here.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small strings; for larger data use `SecureStorage` or file I/O.
- Call `ClearDraft()` after the user explicitly saves or discards the note.
